tory of ideas traces changing conceptions and representations of space by looking at the roles played by writers, artists, commercial publishers, and the Shogunal government in helping to fashion a new awareness of space and place in this period. Her impressively researched study shows how spatial and geographical knowledge confined to elites in early Japan became more generalized, flexible, and widespread in the Tokugawa period. In the broadest sense, her book grasps the elusive processes through which people came to name, to know, and to interpret their worlds in narrative and visual forms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEthnopsychologyzJapan. 0aNational characteristics, Japanese. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  acartography.  acommercial publishers.  aearly modern japan.  aeast asia.  aencyclopedia.  ageographical knowledge.  ageography.  agesaku.  agovernment power.  ajapan.  ajapanese history.  ajapanese studies.  amapmaking.  amaps.  amodern japan.  anational identity.  anonfiction.  apoetry.  apopular culture.  apopular fiction.  apower of maps.  arealm.  arepresentation of space.  asamurai.  asatire comics.  asatire.  asense of space.  ashogunal.  ashogunate.  asocial commentary.  aspace and place.  aspace theory.  atokugawa edo period.  atokugawa.  atravel writing.  atravel.  atravelogue.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023269340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092830540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520928305423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520928305/original  a978-3-11-06